segments.text: This is an interview with O.D.
Butler, Brigadier General, United States Army, retired.
This is the first interview in the series, Aggies to Generals.
Today's date is July 23, 1980.
This is Terry Anderson.
This is a test.
Testing, testing.
This is an interview with Brigadier General Ogborn Duke Butler.
Today is July 23, 1980.
This is Terry Anderson.
Now, you were born on September 29, 1918, in Orange, Texas.
Let's first talk about your upbringing.
Can you tell us about your parents, your father's occupation?
Sure.
My father and mother both originated in Smith County near Crook, Texas.
He after finishing high school became engaged in accounting for some lumber firms.
After he and my mother married they
went to Louisiana to work with people in the turpentine industry and later on then moved to Orange County where he was engaged in the lumber business with three different sawmills and a box factory.
This business failed in 1929.
He used his skills in accounting
and knowledge of real estate to obtain a position with the Tax Assessor Collector of Orange County, where he was Chief Deputy.
Later, upon retirement of Mr. Charles Cottle, the Tax Assessor Collector, he ran for the office and then for more than 20 years he was re-elected, usually
had no opponent.
He was the tax assessor collector for Orange County.
Your father was a tax assessor collector?
Yes, he was.
He held that office when he died of a heart attack at age 61 in 1948 on a deer hunt up in Hill Country, Texas.
Could you tell us about your mother?
My mother was a jarvish.
Jarvis family was an extremely prolific one over in East Texas.
I believe that her father had 17 brothers and sisters.
Some of them had brothers.
So I'm a distant relative who seems like half the people over in East Texas.
On the Jarvis side of the family,
Her father was also engaged in business and worked with the packing industry.
Later, he migrated to Fort Worth and worked in office management for the packing industry.
Retired in Fort Worth.
My mother is still living.
She's 92.
years old and still active.
She lives with her sister in Dallas, Texas, not very far from my sister up in northeast Dallas.
How many siblings did you have?
Well I had two brothers and a sister.
My sister was five years older
My brother, older brother two years older who came to Texas A&M the same year I did and we graduated together from Texas A&M and then a younger brother who was class of 1945.
That class of course got called into the service prior to their graduation.
He did
get his commission and was serving as a second lieutenant platoon leader and was killed in action in France in December of 1944.
During the Battle of the Bulge?
Well it was, yes, his
division, the 45th division I believe it was, arrived during the Battle of the Bulge and they were committed piecemeal in southern France.
So it was during that December period with the stress of the Battle of the Bulge that the infantry got committed even before their artillery got there.
It was probably a rash
young second lieutenant leading his battalion, got killed by a sniper, we were told.
First week he was in combat.
Concerning your parents, could you sort of describe them?
What type of people were they?
Well, I'd say that they were hard-working, very frugal, conservative, Anglo-Saxon Protestant.
people, kind of old south type from over in East Texas.
My father's father died fairly young also and he was a butcher in Troop, Texas.
My father's mother
grandmother on my father's side continued to reside in troop with one of her daughters.
So as a kid we used to visit them fairly often.
That is once or twice a year.
When did your relatives first come to Texas?
Gee I don't know that.
Most Texans know that immediately.
I have a couple of friends in the history department now on this company that have their original land grant from Mexico.
Quite proud of it.
What do you mean by the fact that your parents were conservative?
Well, maybe I should say that they were thrifty on the one side, and that was, I guess, as much by necessity as otherwise.
We never had very much money.
but they of course were homeowners and they were for I might say God, country, the basic things that made America great.
Do you think that your father's political career had much effect on you?
Well, I guess it might have made me a little bit cynical early about politics.
Sometime when he ran for office, I got exposed early to the business of politics related to innuendos and untruths and campaigning and all that bit.
Of course, it has given me a kind of a cynical attitude about politics, all right.
Okay, what religion,
What religion, obviously, then was important in your upbringing?
What religion was it?
Well, it's very strange that my mother was a Baptist and attended the First Baptist Church.
My father was a leader in the First Methodist Church in Orange.
These churches were only a couple of blocks apart.
We attended church regularly, but
During the time, of course, my mother was busy with the children.

My father took the older children to church, so it happened that she was the only Baptist, turned out to be the only Baptist in the family, and all of the children were raised in the Methodist church.
That is unusual.
Now, were there episodes in your early life that you think might have some influence on your future success?
Well of course my father was a very hard-working man, loved the land.
We lived in a suburban area in Orange County where we had livestock, had horses and cattle all my life.
We also were fairly large in the
vegetable production, that is, for just a family type operation.

We would farm about 10 acres for vegetables, much of it hand labor, which my father and the boys would do early in the morning a lot of times, daylight before you'd go to work at 8 o'clock, and we'd go to school.
Of course, we were engaged in that on
and I'm sure that early on I developed a real strong interest in livestock, not only with our own but with other livestock producers in Orange County.
My uncle, my mother's brother was there and an employee of the local meat packing company.
So I used to go with him some out to the little meat packing company.
I think that was contributed to the early interest I had in the meats business.
I was going to ask you about how you became interested in animal science.
Now as far as your parents are concerned, it's obvious that you've had a very successful career.
What ways do you think that your parents are responsible for that?
Well, I think they're very much responsible for it.

developing high standards of performance in school all right from the start, elementary school to high school, and then encouraging responsibility and insisting on responsibility all along related to our livestock business, our little farming enterprises.
that sort of thing.
Can we shift to your early education?
Pardon?
Can we shift now to your early education?
Could you tell me about your early education?
Well the rural schools in Orange County in those days were not very good so my father paid tuition for all of his children to attend
schools in town.
He would drop the kids off at elementary school or high school on his way to work.
Early on after we became older we'd ride bicycles along the way.
Now was this to attend private schools or the public schools in town?
Public schools in town as uh instead of attending
rural school in those days in our district where we lived.
And all of the children in our family had real fine records in elementary, high school, in Orange County.
What were your favorite subjects?
Well, I guess math, biology, not history.
It's kind of funny though, isn't it, that you describe your parents as being patriotic, yet you're not interested in American history.
Well, I'm interested.
I would not say I'm uninterested, but I guess I was active outside with livestock, with sports and other things, and I guess
was not inspired with all the time it took to read and study history.
That's really the basic reason I thought.
Never have been uninterested in it but just haven't been as inspired with that as some other subjects.
Of course we had vocational agriculture in high school and I took all of that and was influenced some by the
teacher of vocational agriculture, there's no question that he's the one that was a former student of Texas A&M.
Oh really, what was his name?
His name was Garden Hart, H-A-R-T.
He actually is the one that inspired me to enroll in agricultural engineering, that's what his degree was in, as well as vocational.
education or agricultural education.
So oddly enough, I started out at Texas A&M as an engineer.
An agricultural engineer.
That was my initial major.
Oh, we're going to get to A&M in a minute.
Let's stay back here.
How about high school?
What high school did you go to?
To Orange High School.
There was just one high school in the city.
And your favorite subjects then were still biology and
Mathematics, English, biology and vocational agriculture.
What kind of student were you?
Well I had very acceptable grades.
I don't know, over 90 average in high school.
But actually I'd have to say not a whole lot of effort.
I had a very strange kind of an ambition.
That is that I'd get all the way through high school and never take a book home.
So we had study hall periods.
I did all of the work required for homework and everything in study halls in high school.
I actually double promoted three times along the way and the last time didn't work.
I don't remember exactly what grade it was in, maybe about fifth grade.
I remember when I double promoted I got in that class and it was way over my head and I resisted that and so I was put back.
So actually I skipped one grade.
But at this time, correct me if I'm wrong, didn't schools, you were promoted half grades at a time?
Half grades, sure.
So I actually graduated from high school at age 16.
A year early then?
A year early.
Of course there were only 11 grades in the public schools then.
So I got a degree, a high school diploma at age 16.
Oh that's strong.
What activities were you interested in or participated in in high school?
I participated in the sports activities and then the activities related to vocational agriculture.
The 4-H?
Not 4-H, FFA.
So I did in high school during vacation period work with the county agricultural agent and mapping farms around county one year.
So I did get exposed to the county extension agent in Orange County during my career.
What sports?
Primarily basketball.
I was a little fella.
I did later in football.
I was like a hundred and twenty-five, thirty pound halfback.
Not very good, but I did later in football.
Did your head get stepped on quite a few times?
Yeah.
I was associated with the famous Hilliard family in Arnie County, the youngest one of those Hilliards.
was a teammate on football.
He never made it quite as big in the University of Texas as his older brothers did, who were very famous football players for the University of Texas.
In the F and the Future Farmers of America, did you participate in any leadership positions?
Yes.
I was an officer in the FFA chapter.
I've forgotten exactly which one of the officer positions I held.
I did participate in judging activities, made a team that went to the Houston livestock show.
Really?
We didn't.
do any good in the state judging contests, but through basketball and FFA activities I was, I did travel around to the other communities in that district.
So it seems then that you were, that you started a position of leadership or responsibility fairly early in life.
Do you agree with that or disagree?
Well I'd say that I certainly wasn't a very dominant leader in high school times.
Well can you explain that?
Well I was younger, a year younger than most of my classmates and while I participated in things
I wasn't good enough at sports to be dominant at all.
I got academic recognition along in the classes.
I'd say it's kind of an average career in high school.
Would you consider yourself popular in high school?
I guess so.
Okay.
You graduated at the age of 16 and this was right in the middle of the depression, wasn't it?
Yeah, is it over?
How did the Great Depression affect your life and your family's lives?
Well it was very traumatic in 1929 when my father went broke
lumber business and box factory business.
He elected not to take bankruptcy but to pay off his debts so that was a burden on our family for years for him to pay off the debts that had been incurred with his business failure.
I don't think it hurt us at all.
We did learn to sacrifice, never lag for food.
We certainly were not extravagant in clothing at all or in entertainment, but that's the way all our peers were too, so we didn't know anybody.
And I'm certain that some sacrifices along there helped demold character for my brothers and me.
We knew what it was to be denied things.
Yeah, yeah.
Would you think that this has an increased possibility of making you want to save money, or?
I'm not sure what your thoughts, but.
There's no question that that certainly made me conservative about financial matters.
It seemed to have approximately the same effect on my father.
Were any of your, what was your older brother for example, did he join the CCC's or any New Deal programs?
Did you benefit in any way from any New Deal programs?
No.
My sister was an outstanding student in high school.
My brother had about the same kind of high school record I had.
When he graduated from high school, he went to work.
Both my sister and my brother worked at a casket factory in Orange.
So we were making it on our own without any kind of subsidy program at all.
Was one of the reasons your father went into politics because of the 1929 crash and the fact that it had on his job?
Well, there's no question about that, that when his business failed, he looked for an opportunity to use his accounting and business skills
and his knowledge of real estate.
And of course the opportunity was there to be Chief Deputy Tax Assessor Collector.
He had of course established contact with that office and his lumber dealings around and leasing land for timber and purchase of land and that sort of thing.
It was a sort of a natural relationship to the job he had done since timber was so important in Orange County area at that time.
Did the depression have an effect not only on your father but on your mother?
Well mother was a homebody.
Her social life was around the church and
our relatives, her brother and his wife that also lived in Orange County.
I would say that she was such a conservative person along there that for instance she never learned to drive an automobile in her whole life.
Why was that?
Can you explain that?
I think she was a retiring homemaker type.
She stayed home, took care of the kids, did the cooking and chores like that that homemakers were expected to do.
She never had to learn.
She was an intelligent woman, but my father was a pretty dominant kind of a fellow.
He pretty well made the decisions related to the family all right.
early on.
She didn't go anywhere much that he didn't go so she didn't need to be able to drive an automobile.
There weren't any automobiles when she was a young girl when she would normally would have learned to drive which she just never did.
Learned to drive and just never to this day.
Was your
father a Democrat?
Yes, he was.
And was he a Roosevelt man?
Well, I would say that he was not a blind supporter of the Democratic Party.
I think he liked certain aspects of the Roosevelt regime, but was not fascinated with other aspects.
welfare part of it, the socialistic part of it, he was not fascinated with at all.
He couldn't stomach Al Smith, so I'm sure when Al Smith ran for presidency, he didn't vote for Al Smith or support him, so I would say that
In certain ways, he was an independent, but he always ran on the Democratic ticket, because everybody else did in Texas during that period.
Absolutely, absolutely.
Did his politics and his being a member of the Democratic Party have an influence on your future politics?
No, I don't think so.
He's good.
help us to analyze issues and support people rather than parties.
So he did not try to influence us, any of the children, to be party members, but to be rather independent thinkers.
And I suspect that's what our people, all of our family members are without being committed to one political party or another.
But he talked issues with his sons?
Oh no question, sure.
I bet you that was stimulating.
He was a fine companion to his sons.
He was an ardent hunter and fisherman, so he took us hunting and fishing very often.
Spent a lot of time with his sons.
and of course a lot of time working too, that is outside of his office hours and with our livestock and with our truck farming operations.
But all the colleges in Texas and in the nation, why'd you come to A&M?
Was it because of your high school teacher primarily?
Or were there other reasons?
Well, we were
inclined some toward agriculture.
A big thing in our county during those days was for people to come to the Farm at Home Week at Texas A&M.
So many of my friends and their families would come here.
We had a lot of activities related to
home demonstration agents and county agents, food preservation, canning, things like that.
So Texas A&M was just an extremely dominant type association in the county.
And certainly we didn't have any wide acquaintanceship with other universities.
I suppose we never even seriously considered any other institution.
You never considered an alternative like LSU or?
Oh no, think about a state.
Tuition probably.
That's right, of course Lamar State University, Lamar, we were just getting started in Beaumont, Jefferson County.
a reputation that was anywhere comparable to Texas A&M.
Of course, the two universities in our county that were real dominant were Texas A&M and the University of Texas.
The dominant wealthy people in the county were supporters of the University of Texas.
Orange had a real strong orientation toward the University of Texas.
H.J.
Ledger Stark was one of the major supporters of the University of Texas financially.
We had a number of varsity football players.
But I'm sure that the primary influence I had were from the county extension agent and the vocational teacher, the teacher of vocational agriculture.
Both good Texas Aggies.
plus the fact that you enjoyed working with the animals on your small spread.
Yes, that's right.
Did your father boost education?
He had a high school degree.
